definitions: showing smug or uncritical satisfaction with oneself or one's achievements
examples: The team became complacent after winning several games
Don't be complacent about your health check results

definitions: showing or expressing dissatisfaction, annoyance, or unhappiness about something
examples: The complaining customer demanded to speak with the manager
She adopted a complaining tone when discussing her workload

definitions: combining in such a way as to enhance or emphasize the qualities of each other
given or supplied free of charge as a courtesy or favor
examples: The two artists had complementary skills that made them great partners
Their complementary personalities created a balanced relationship
The hotel offered complementary breakfast to all guests
We received complementary tickets to the concert

definitions: having been finished or brought to an end with all necessary parts done
examples: The completed project was delivered ahead of schedule
She submitted her completed application form yesterday

definitions: currently finishing or making whole by adding what is lacking or needed
examples: The completing phase of construction will take two months
Students are busy completing their final assignments

definitions: meeting or willing to meet specified standards, rules, or laws
examples: The company ensures all products are compliant with safety regulations
She was always compliant with her doctor's instructions

definitions: involved with others in illegal activity or wrongdoing, especially as an accomplice
examples: The accountant was complicit in the financial fraud scheme
They were complicit in covering up the safety violations

definitions: expressing a compliment, conveying or containing praise and approval
given or supplied free of charge as a courtesy or promotional gesture
examples: She made several complimentary remarks about his presentation
The review was highly complimentary of the restaurant's service
The airline offers complimentary beverages during the flight
Guests receive complimentary access to the fitness center

definitions: having one's feelings and expression under control, calm and confident
having been created or written, consisting of various elements or parts
examples: She remained composed despite the stressful situation
The diplomat appeared composed during the tense negotiations
The committee is composed of experts from various fields
This piece was composed by Mozart in his early years

definitions: made up of various parts or elements combined into a single entity
examples: The composite material is stronger than its individual components
They created a composite image from multiple photographs

definitions: relating to the way something is put together or the act of creating music or art
examples: The artist's compositional techniques create visual harmony
We studied the compositional structure of classical symphonies

definitions: made worse or more intense by additional factors or circumstances
formed by combining two or more elements, parts, or ingredients together
examples: The problem was compounded by poor communication
His anxiety was compounded by lack of sleep
The medicine contains several compounded ingredients
Interest is compounded monthly on this savings account

definitions: able to be understood clearly, intelligible and making sense to the mind
examples: The instructions were written in comprehensible language
Her explanation made the complex theory comprehensible

definitions: pressed together or forced into less space by external pressure
reduced in size, duration, or extent while maintaining essential information
examples: The compressed air powered the pneumatic tools
The injury resulted from compressed nerve tissue
The compressed file takes up less storage space
They delivered a compressed version of the presentation

definitions: capable of being pressed or squeezed into a smaller space or volume
examples: Air is highly compressible compared to water
The compressible foam adjusts to body shape

definitions: revealing something embarrassing or damaging, especially to someone's reputation
involving or willing to make concessions by mutual agreement
examples: The leaked photos put her in a compromising position
He avoided any compromising situations at work
They adopted a compromising approach to resolve the conflict
Both parties showed compromising attitudes during negotiations

definitions: resulting from or acting on an irresistible urge, often against one's conscious wishes
examples: His compulsive behavior required professional treatment
She's a compulsive shopper who can't resist sales

definitions: required by law or rule to be done, obligatory rather than voluntary
examples: Education is compulsory for children up to age sixteen
The company introduced compulsory safety training sessions

definitions: relating to or using calculation, especially performed by computers or mathematical methods
examples: The research requires significant computational resources
She specializes in computational linguistics and language processing

definitions: having an outline or surface that curves inward like the interior of a bowl
examples: The concave mirror focused light to a single point
The spoon has a concave surface for holding liquid

definitions: kept secret or hidden from view, not allowed to be seen or known
examples: The concealed weapon was discovered during the search
She kept her emotions carefully concealed from others

definitions: keeping something secret or preventing it from being known or seen
examples: The concealing makeup covered all her blemishes perfectly
His concealing behavior made everyone suspicious

definitions: excessively proud of oneself, having an exaggerated sense of self-importance
examples: His conceited attitude made him unpopular with colleagues
She became conceited after winning the beauty contest

definitions: capable of being imagined, understood, or believed as possible or probable
examples: It's conceivable that prices could drop next year
Every conceivable option was considered before deciding

definitions: gathered together or focused in one place or on one thing
made denser or stronger by removing water or other diluting agents
examples: The troops were concentrated along the eastern border
She gave the problem her concentrated attention
Add water to the concentrated juice before drinking
The concentrated detergent requires only small amounts

definitions: having a common center, as circles or spheres arranged one inside another
examples: The target consists of concentric circles around a bullseye
Tree rings form concentric patterns showing annual growth

definitions: relating to or based on mental concepts rather than physical objects or specific examples
examples: The artist created conceptual pieces exploring identity
We need a conceptual framework before starting development

definitions: jointly arranged, planned, or carried out in cooperation with others
examples: They made a concerted effort to improve customer service
The concerted campaign resulted in policy changes

definitions: intended to placate or pacify, showing willingness to end a disagreement
examples: He adopted a conciliatory tone after the argument
The company made conciliatory gestures to striking workers

definitions: giving information clearly and in few words, brief but comprehensive
examples: Please provide a concise summary of the report
Her concise writing style makes complex topics accessible

definitions: having been brought to an end or settled with finality
examples: The concluded negotiations resulted in a fair agreement
The police considered the case concluded after arrests

definitions: serving to bring something to an end or form a final part
examples: The concluding chapter summarizes all key findings
In her concluding remarks, she thanked the audience

definitions: proving something decisively, putting an end to debate or question
examples: The DNA evidence was conclusive in solving the case
They found conclusive proof of the theory's validity

definitions: naturally accompanying or associated with something else as a consequence or related phenomenon
examples: Increased traffic is a concomitant effect of urban growth
The medication has several concomitant side effects

definitions: existing, happening, or operating at the same time in parallel
examples: She's taking three concurrent courses this semester
The judge imposed concurrent sentences for both crimes

definitions: agreeing with something or happening at the same time as something else
examples: The concurring opinions supported the majority decision
Several concurring events led to the crisis

definitions: expressing complete disapproval of something, typically in public and formally
examples: His condemning remarks about the policy sparked debate
The report contained condemning evidence against the company

definitions: showing feelings of superiority, being patronizing or talking down to others
examples: His condescending tone irritated everyone in the meeting
She gave a condescending smile to the junior employee

definitions: subject to one or more conditions being met before taking effect
examples: The offer is conditional upon passing the background check
They received conditional approval for the loan

definitions: trained to behave in a certain way or respond to particular stimuli
brought into a desired state or made suitable for use
examples: The dog was conditioned to respond to voice commands
Years of practice had conditioned her reflexes
The athlete's conditioned body could endure extreme stress
This conditioned air keeps the room comfortable

definitions: making a certain situation or outcome likely or possible, contributing to
examples: A quiet environment is conducive to studying
The warm climate is conducive to outdoor activities

definitions: able to transmit heat, electricity, or sound through a material
examples: Copper is highly conductive and ideal for electrical wiring
The conductive gel improves electrode contact with skin

definitions: united in a league, alliance, or conspiracy for common purpose
examples: The confederate states formed a unified defense system
Several confederate nations signed the trade agreement

definitions: intended to be kept secret, entrusted with private or restricted information
examples: The confidential documents were kept in a locked safe
She shared confidential information with her lawyer

definitions: arranged or set up in a particular way for specific purpose or function
examples: The computer was configured for maximum performance
Each workspace is configured to meet individual needs

definitions: restricted within limits, kept within a bounded space or scope
examples: The patient was confined to bed for several weeks
The discussion was confined to budgetary matters only

definitions: restricting someone or something within limits or preventing freedom of movement
examples: The confining space made everyone feel claustrophobic
She found the strict rules confining and oppressive

definitions: serving to confirm, establish, or support the truth or accuracy of something
examples: The lab ran confirmatory tests on the initial results
We received confirmatory evidence supporting our hypothesis

definitions: established as true, valid, or genuine beyond doubt through evidence or testimony
examples: The confirmed cases of flu increased during winter
She's a confirmed vegetarian who never eats meat

definitions: establishing the truth, accuracy, or validity of something previously uncertain
examples: The confirming data supported our initial hypothesis
We're still confirming details of the incident
